liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Oil and gas giant Santos has also reported its half-yearly earnings this morning, with its profit after tax down by almost a third to $US790 million ($1.23 billion). Last year, Santos reported a half-year profit of $US1.17 billion. The company's production volume was down by 13% to 45 million barrels of oil equivalent, and sales volume also fell by 15% to 41.7 million barrels of oil equivalent. Sales revenue also fell by 21 per cent, which Santos said was the result of lower realised prices for oil and gas. Despite the fall in profits, Santos will pay a dividend of 8.7 US cents per share, which it says is 14% higher than the previous year's results.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Sam Burgess' time at South Sydney appears to be at an end after the Rabbitohs assistant coach left training early on Wednesday morning. Burgess indicated he would make a statement in due course after leaving the club's training centre this morning but said: "I wish the boys all the well (sic)." Club chairman Nick Pappas left soon after Burgess and said: "We wish Sam all the best." Burgess — a club legend who holds a close bond with club co-owner Russell Crowe — has clashed with head coach Jason Demetriou. Burgess is set to join Super League club Warrington next year. Reporting by AAP

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese's office has confirmed he'll announce the date for the Voice to Parliament referendum at an event in Adelaide on Wednesday next week. The prime minister has previously said the vote would happen in October or November. Australians will vote either 'yes' or 'no' on whether a Voice – which would act as an independent advisory body for First Nations people – should be enshrined in the constitution. It is widly tipped the date will be October 14, however the actual date of the referendum has not been confirmed.
